lay. For a</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> heavyweight building</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> you pay a bit of a penalty of 4% embodied CO</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> footprint, but that is paid back in just 11 years and that is</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a residential property. The payback period is probably a year in something as sophisticated as this building. Buil</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ding regulations have</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a role to play. SAP at the moment is a </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">little bit crude, not so sophisticated, particularly th</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">e overheating check in SAP. W</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ith a review of building regulations</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a more long-term focu</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">s on the built environment, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">we stand a chance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Jim Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: You have to be careful with building regulations. They are s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">pecifically written </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">for new properties</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> in the main</span><span style="font